## Supabase Types
- Real generated types are in `src/types/database.ts` (1931 lines, generated from live DB)
- Supabase project ID: `vnlclwwhtuxwwnkvmiqn`
- To regenerate types after schema changes, run (PowerShell):
  ```
  $env:SUPABASE_ACCESS_TOKEN = (Get-Content .env.local | Select-String "SUPABASE_ACCESS_TOKEN").ToString().Split("=")[1]
  npx supabase gen types typescript --project-id vnlclwwhtuxwwnkvmiqn > src/types/database.ts
  ```
- The access token is stored in `.env.local` as `SUPABASE_ACCESS_TOKEN` (never commit this)

## Language Rules
- **ALL user-facing text MUST be in English** — no Dutch, no mixed languages
- This applies to: UI labels, buttons, navigation, error messages, empty states, tooltips, placeholders, notifications, email templates, and any text visible to users
- Code comments and variable names may remain in English (they already are)
- The only exception: data stored in the database by the user themselves (e.g. game names, order notes)

## Design Rules
1. Dark mode default. Deep dark backgrounds (#09090b), indigo primary, amber CTAs
2. NEVER use generic AI aesthetics (no Inter font, no purple gradients on white)
3. Use 'Cal Sans' for headings, 'Satoshi' for body text, 'JetBrains Mono' for data
4. Subtle glassmorphism on elevated cards (backdrop-blur-xl + bg-white/5)
5. Glow effects on interactive elements (box-shadow with primary at 15% opacity)
6. Skeleton loaders for ALL loading states — NEVER use spinners
7. Framer Motion for page transitions (fade + slide, 200ms)
8. All empty states must have a custom illustration + clear CTA
9. Mobile-first responsive. Min 44px tap targets
10. Make it look like a senior designer built it, not AI

## Code Rules
1. TypeScript strict mode — no `any` types, no type assertions unless necessary
2. Server Components by default, Client Components only when needed ('use client')
3. ALL database queries via server components or API routes, never client-side direct
4. Supabase RLS on ALL tables — always verify auth in API routes too
5. Zod schemas for ALL form validation AND API input validation
6. Error boundaries on every route group (error.tsx)
7. Loading states on every route group (loading.tsx)
8. TanStack Query for client-side data fetching (staleTime: 30s default)
9. ALL price calculations server-side (never trust client calculations)
10. Sensitive data (tokens, credentials, API keys) always encrypted at rest
11. Activity logging for ALL admin actions
12. Optimistic updates for real-time features (order progress, chat)

## File Naming
- Components: PascalCase (GameCard.tsx, ServiceConfigurator.tsx)
- Utilities: camelCase (formatCurrency.ts, slugify.ts)
- Types: PascalCase (OrderStatus, WorkerTier)
- Validators: camelCase matching entity (order.ts, game.ts)
- Database columns: snake_case (order_status, tier_id)
- API routes: kebab-case paths (/api/orders/[id]/claim)
- CSS variables: kebab-case (--color-primary, --bg-card)

## Component Patterns
- Use composition over prop drilling
- Shared UI components in /components/ui/
- Domain components in /components/{domain}/
- Each component file exports ONE default component
- Co-locate component-specific types in the same file
- Use forwardRef for interactive components that may need refs

## Data Fetching Patterns
- Server Components: direct Supabase queries (createServerClient)
- Client Components: TanStack Query hooks calling API routes
- Mutations: TanStack Query useMutation with optimistic updates
- Real-time: Supabase Realtime subscriptions via custom hooks
- Pagination: cursor-based for infinite scroll, offset for data tables

## Security Architecture Rules (CRITICAL — never violate)
1. **NEVER use `createAdminClient()` or `createServiceClient()` in customer/worker pages or layouts.**
   - Customer and worker routes MUST use `createClient()` (user-scoped, cookie-based) so RLS enforces access.
   - `createServiceClient()` / `createAdminClient()` is ONLY allowed in:
     - `/app/api/admin/` routes (after verifying `is_admin()`)
     - `/app/api/worker/` routes for system-level writes (after verifying role)
     - Server-side admin page components in `/app/(admin)/`
2. **NEVER use the service role key in `middleware.ts`.**
   - Middleware runs on Edge runtime — use the anon key with user session cookies.
   - Role checks in middleware must use the user-scoped client (RLS applies).
3. **NEVER expose debug endpoints in production.**
   - Any route that returns cookies, user IDs, env var previews, or internal state must be gated: `if (process.env.NODE_ENV === "production") return 404`.
   - Prefer deleting debug routes entirely after use.
4. **ALL admin PATCH/POST/DELETE API routes MUST validate input with a Zod schema.**
   - No direct `body` pass-through to `.update(body)` — always use an explicit allowlist of fields.
   - Enum fields (status, role, type) must use `z.enum([...])` with the exact allowed values.
5. **Order/resource ownership must be enforced in the query, not after.**
   - Bad: fetch with admin client, then check `if (order.customer_id !== user.id)`.
   - Good: `.eq("customer_id", user.id)` in the query itself with user-scoped client.
6. **TypeScript: no `as unknown as` casts to silence Supabase type errors.**
   - Use generated Database types (`@/types/database`) and typed clients.
   - If a type mismatch exists, fix the type — don't cast around it.

## Supabase Client Usage Guide
| Context | Client to use | Why |
|---|---|---|
| Customer/worker server pages | `createClient()` from `@/lib/supabase/server` | User-scoped, RLS enforced |
| Admin server pages | `createServiceClient()` from `@/lib/supabase/server` | Needs full access, server-only |
| Admin API routes | `createServiceClient()` after admin check | Bypass RLS only after auth verify |
| Middleware | `createServerClient()` with anon key + cookies | Edge runtime, no service key |
| Client components | `createBrowserClient()` from `@/lib/supabase/client` | Browser, anon key only |

## Security Checklist (verify for every feature)
- [ ] RLS policy exists for the table
- [ ] API route checks auth (getUser())
- [ ] API route validates input with Zod schema (explicit field allowlist)
- [ ] Customer/worker pages use user-scoped client (NOT admin/service client)
- [ ] Ownership enforced in query (`.eq("customer_id", user.id)`), not after fetch
- [ ] No debug endpoints left in production
- [ ] Sensitive data is encrypted
- [ ] Admin actions are logged to activity_log
- [ ] Rate limiting on public endpoints
- [ ] CSRF protection via Supabase auth tokens
- [ ] No secrets in client-side code
- [ ] No `as unknown as` type casts — use proper Database types
